<h2 class="header"><i>11</i>Extra credit<a class="headerlink" href="#extra-credit" name="extra-credit">&para;</a></h2>
<blockquote>
<p>Show that there is no surjective homomorphism from <span>$\mathbb Z_2[x]$</span> to the ring <span>$\mathbb Z_2 \times \mathbb Z_2 \times \mathbb Z_2$</span>.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Suppose there is a surjective homomorphism. Then <span>$\exists a,b \in \mathbb{GL}_2(\mathbb Z_2)$</span> satisfying <span>$\Phi(a) = \Phi(b) = c$</span>, where <span>$c$</span> is some element of <span>$\mathbb Z_2 \times \mathbb Z_2 \times \mathbb Z_2$</span>.</p>
<p>It follows that:<br />
<span>$\Phi(a) + \Phi(b) = 2c$</span>Â¸<br />
But all elements of <span>$\mathbb Z_2 \times \mathbb Z_2 \times \mathbb Z_2$</span> are order 2, so <span>$2c = 0$</span></p>
<p>By the definition of a homomorphism, addition is preserved, so we must also have:<br />
<span>$\Phi(a+b) = 2c = 0$</span></p>
<p>A homomorphism must also map zero to itself, so we conclude that <span>$a + b = 0$</span>.<br />
<span>$a$</span> must be the additive inverse of <span>$b$</span>, but we see that in <span>$\mathbb Z_2[x]$</span> every element is its own additive inverse (try it).</p>
<p>Thus we conclude that <span>$a = b$</span>, a contradiction if <span>$\Phi$</span> is surjective.</p>
<h3 class="header"><i>11.1</i>Accuracy and discussion<a class="headerlink" href="#accuracy-and-discussion_10" name="accuracy-and-discussion_10">&para;</a></h3>
<p>Should be fine.</p>
	
